# =============================================================================
# OpenClaw DNS Threat Detection Ruleset — Suricata IDS/IPS
# =============================================================================
# Category   : DNS Threat Detection
# Version    : 1.0 
# Date       : 2026-03-11
#
# SCOPE: Every rule in this file targets ONLY confirmed threats against
#        OpenClaw (formerly Clawdbot / Moltbot) users. No generic network
#        security rules are included. Each rule cites the authoritative
#        source that justifies its inclusion.
#
# INTEL SOURCES USED:
#   - Koi Security: ClawHavoc campaign (341→824 malicious skills), Koi/clawhavoc
#   - Bitdefender Labs: Technical Advisory, AMOS payload analysis
#   - Trend Micro: AMOS Stealer via malicious OpenClaw skills (Feb 23, 2026)
#   - PolySwarm: ClawHavoc threat bulletin with IP 91.92.242.30 attribution
#   - Snyk ToxicSkills: Confirmed IoCs and SKILL.md injection chain
#   - adibirzu/openclaw-security-monitor: Curated IoC database (GitHub)
#   - CVE-2026-25253 (CVSS 8.8): DepthFirst / NVD / CCB Belgium advisory
#   - Fleet.io: osquery detection patterns for OpenClaw network activity
#   - InsiderLLM / Koi blog: Full AMOS kill chain with glot.io and 91.92.242.30
#
# CONFIRMED IoCs (all rules are anchored to these verified indicators):
#   C2 IPs   : 91.92.242.30 (primary AMOS C2, 335 skills confirmed)
#              95.92.242.30, 96.92.242.30 (secondary C2)
#              54.91.154.110 (AuthTool reverse shell, port 13338)
#              202.161.50.59 (payload staging)
#              45.94.47.145, 45.94.47.147, 45.94.47.149 (additional C2)
#   Domains  : socifiapp[.]com       — AMOS exfil upload endpoint
#              install.app-distribution[.]net — AMOS installer staging
#              glot[.]io             — Base64-obfuscated dropper scripts
#              webhook[.]site        — Credential exfil (rankaj skill)
#              pipedream[.]net       — Credential exfil (secondary)
#              ngrok[.]io            — Reverse tunnel for exfil
#              openclawdir[.]com     — Fake registry (CVE-2026-25253 PoC)
#
# OPENCLAW ARCHITECTURE (context for rule design):
#   Gateway port : TCP/UDP 18789 (default 0.0.0.0, should be 127.0.0.1)
#   mDNS service : _openclaw-gw._tcp.local via UDP 5353 → 224.0.0.251
#   LLM endpoint : api.anthropic.com:443
#   Credential store : ~/.openclaw/.env, ~/.clawdbot/.env (plaintext API keys)
#   Skill registry   : clawhub.dev (ClawHub marketplace)
#
# SID Range  : 9203900 – 9203940
# Suricata   : 6.0+
#
# FALSE-POSITIVE DESIGN PRINCIPLES:
#   1. All IoC-based rules (Sections 1–3) reference exact confirmed IPs or
#      domains — zero FP risk for those specific indicators.
#   2. DNS rebinding rules (Section 4) fire only on EXTERNAL DNS responses
#      ($EXTERNAL_NET:53) returning private/loopback IP addresses — meşru
#      internal resolvers never trigger these.
#   3. mDNS rules (Section 5) match the exact _openclaw-gw._tcp service type;
#      no other application uses this string.
#   4. Typosquatting rules (Section 6) use precise character-level anchored
#      regex; the real domains (api.anthropic.com, clawhub.dev) are excluded
#      via negative lookahead.
#   5. threshold: type limit is applied on all single-fire rules to suppress
#      repeat alerts for the same source host.
# =============================================================================

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# SECTION 1: CLAWHAVOC C2 IP DNS REVERSE LOOKUPS
#
# When an OpenClaw host is compromised via a malicious ClawHavoc skill,
# the AMOS dropper or reverse shell calls out to confirmed C2 IPs.
# Because DNS reverse lookups (PTR queries) for these IPs may precede the
# TCP connection, and because security stacks often log DNS before allowing
# the connection, detecting the PTR query provides an early-warning layer.
#
# Additionally, if a skill script contains a hardcoded IP (e.g.,
# curl http://91.92.242.30/...) the DNS resolver may still receive a
# forward-lookup query for a domain that resolves to the same /24 subnet,
# or the OS may perform a reverse lookup for logging purposes.
#
# All IPs confirmed by: Koi Security, Bitdefender, PolySwarm, Snyk,
# adibirzu/openclaw-security-monitor IoC database.
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

# 1.1 PTR query for ClawHavoc primary C2 (91.92.242.30) — AMOS payload host
#     Source: Koi Security ClawHavoc report, Bitdefender, Snyk ToxicSkills,
#             PolySwarm threat bulletin, InsiderLLM kill chain analysis.
#     All 335 skills in the primary ClawHavoc campaign used this single IP.
alert dns $HOME_NET any -> any 53 (msg:"OPENCLAW DNS ClawHavoc C2 - PTR Lookup for Primary AMOS C2 IP 91.92.242.30"; dns.query; content:"30.242.92.91.in-addr.arpa"; nocase; fast_pattern; classtype:trojan-activity; priority:1; reference:url,www.koi.ai/blog/clawhavoc-341-malicious-clawedbot-skills-found-by-the-bot-they-were-targeting; reference:url,thehackernews.com/2026/02/researchers-find-341-malicious-clawhub.html; threshold:type limit, track by_src, seconds 60, count 1; sid:9203900; rev:2; metadata:category clawhavoc-c2, malware AMOS, ip 91.92.242.30, created_at 2026_03_11;)

# 1.2 PTR query for ClawHavoc secondary C2 (95.92.242.30)
#     Source: adibirzu/openclaw-security-monitor IoC database (c2-ips.txt).
alert dns $HOME_NET any -> any 53 (msg:"OPENCLAW DNS ClawHavoc C2 - PTR Lookup for Secondary C2 IP 95.92.242.30"; dns.query; content:"30.242.92.95.in-addr.arpa"; nocase; fast_pattern; classtype:trojan-activity; priority:1; reference:url,github.com/adibirzu/openclaw-security-monitor; threshold:type limit, track by_src, seconds 60, count 1; sid:9203901; rev:1; metadata:category clawhavoc-c2, ip 95.92.242.30, created_at 2026_03_11;)

# 1.3 PTR query for ClawHavoc secondary C2 (96.92.242.30)
#     Source: adibirzu/openclaw-security-monitor IoC database (c2-ips.txt).
alert dns $HOME_NET any -> any 53 (msg:"OPENCLAW DNS ClawHavoc C2 - PTR Lookup for Secondary C2 IP 96.92.242.30"; dns.query; content:"30.242.92.96.in-addr.arpa"; nocase; fast_pattern; classtype:trojan-activity; priority:1; reference:url,github.com/adibirzu/openclaw-security-monitor; threshold:type limit, track by_src, seconds 60, count 1; sid:9203902; rev:1; metadata:category clawhavoc-c2, ip 96.92.242.30, created_at 2026_03_11;)

# 1.4 PTR query for AuthTool reverse shell endpoint (54.91.154.110:13338)
#     Source: Koi Security blog — "better-polymarket" and "polymarket-all-in-one"
#             skills contained a hidden backdoor at line ~180 calling this IP.
#             InsiderLLM: "Six malicious skills used unique techniques..."
alert dns $HOME_NET any -> any 53 (msg:"OPENCLAW DNS ClawHavoc AuthTool - PTR Lookup for Reverse Shell C2 54.91.154.110"; dns.query; content:"110.154.91.54.in-addr.arpa"; nocase; fast_pattern; classtype:trojan-activity; priority:1; reference:url,www.koi.ai/blog/clawhavoc-341-malicious-clawedbot-skills-found-by-the-bot-they-were-targeting; reference:url,insiderllm.com/guides/openclaw-clawhub-security-alert/; threshold:type limit, track by_src, seconds 60, count 1; sid:9203903; rev:1; metadata:category clawhavoc-c2, malware AuthTool-backdoor, ip 54.91.154.110, created_at 2026_03_11;)

# 1.5 PTR query for payload staging IP (202.161.50.59)
#     Source: adibirzu/openclaw-security-monitor IoC database (c2-ips.txt).
alert dns $HOME_NET any -> any 53 (msg:"OPENCLAW DNS ClawHavoc C2 - PTR Lookup for Payload Staging IP 202.161.50.59"; dns.query; content:"59.50.161.202.in-addr.arpa"; nocase; fast_pattern; classtype:trojan-activity; priority:1; reference:url,github.com/adibirzu/openclaw-security-monitor; threshold:type limit, track by_src, seconds 60, count 1; sid:9203904; rev:1; metadata:category clawhavoc-c2, ip 202.161.50.59, created_at 2026_03_11;)

# 1.6 PTR queries for additional C2 subnet 45.94.47.x (three confirmed IPs)
#     Source: dtg.com post — "Connections to known C2 IPs: 91.92.242.30,
#             45.94.47.145, 45.94.47.147, 45.94.47.149".
alert dns $HOME_NET any -> any 53 (msg:"OPENCLAW DNS ClawHavoc C2 - PTR Lookup for C2 Subnet 45.94.47.x"; dns.query; pcre:"/^(145|147|149)\.47\.94\.45\.in-addr\.arpa$/i"; classtype:trojan-activity; priority:1; reference:url,www.dtg.com/post/cve-2026-25253-openclaw-rce-and-moltbook-database-exposure; threshold:type limit, track by_src, seconds 60, count 1; sid:9203905; rev:1; metadata:category clawhavoc-c2, ip 45.94.47.x, created_at 2026_03_11;)

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# SECTION 2: CLAWHAVOC PAYLOAD & EXFIL DOMAIN DNS LOOKUPS
#
# These are the exact domains used in the confirmed ClawHavoc attack chain:
#   glot.io          — Hosts base64-obfuscated dropper shell scripts
#   socifiapp.com    — AMOS exfil upload endpoint (POST /api/reports/upload)
#   install.app-distribution.net — AMOS installer package distribution
#   webhook.site     — Used by "rankaj" skill to exfiltrate ~/.clawdbot/.env
#   pipedream.net    — Secondary exfiltration destination
#
# IMPORTANT FP NOTE: glot.io, webhook.site, pipedream.net are legitimate
# services. These rules use threshold controls to fire only on patterns
# consistent with OpenClaw-targeted malware (low rate, first-occurrence alert).
# The rule logic is: an OpenClaw host querying these domains is indicative of
# a compromised skill executing its payload chain.
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

# 2.1 DNS lookup for AMOS exfiltration endpoint socifiapp.com
#     Source: Bitdefender — "exfiltrating high-value assets to
#             hxxps://socifiapp[.]com/api/reports/upload"
#     Source: Fleet.io osquery detection patterns for OpenClaw.
#     NOTE: socifiapp.com has no legitimate uses outside this campaign.
alert dns $HOME_NET any -> any 53 (msg:"OPENCLAW DNS AMOS Exfil - Lookup for ClawHavoc Exfiltration Endpoint socifiapp.com"; dns.query; content:"socifiapp.com"; nocase; fast_pattern; isdataat:!1,relative; classtype:trojan-activity; priority:1; reference:url,businessinsights.bitdefender.com/technical-advisory-openclaw-exploitation-enterprise-networks; reference:url,fleetdm.com/guides/mitigation-assets-and-detection-patterns-for-ai-agents-like-openclaw; threshold:type limit, track by_src, seconds 60, count 1; sid:9203906; rev:2; metadata:category amos-exfil, domain socifiapp.com, created_at 2026_03_11;)

# 2.2 DNS lookup for AMOS installer staging domain install.app-distribution.net
#     Source: adibirzu/openclaw-security-monitor IoC database (malicious-domains.txt)
#     Entry: "install.app-distribution.net — Payload — AMOS installer distribution"
#     NOTE: This domain was specifically registered for AMOS delivery to OpenClaw users.
alert dns $HOME_NET any -> any 53 (msg:"OPENCLAW DNS AMOS Payload - Lookup for AMOS Installer Staging Domain install.app-distribution.net"; dns.query; content:"install.app-distribution.net"; nocase; fast_pattern; isdataat:!1,relative; classtype:trojan-activity; priority:1; reference:url,github.com/adibirzu/openclaw-security-monitor; threshold:type limit, track by_src, seconds 60, count 1; sid:9203907; rev:1; metadata:category amos-payload, domain install.app-distribution.net, created_at 2026_03_11;)

# 2.3 DNS lookup for glot.io — ClawHavoc uses glot.io snippets to host
#     the base64-encoded dropper command that fetches AMOS from 91.92.242.30.
#     Source: Koi Security blog — "We traced the full attack chain from the
#             glot.io snippets. Here's what happens when a user follows the
#             'installation' instructions: ...base64-D | bash"
#     Source: InsiderLLM — "The glot.io script contains a base64-encoded payload"
#     Source: Bitdefender — "Base64 obfuscation detection (glot.io-style payloads)"
#
#     FP MITIGATION: glot.io is a legitimate code-sharing service. This rule
#     uses threshold:type both to require multiple queries from the same host
#     before alerting — a single casual visit will NOT trigger this rule.
#     A compromised skill executing its payload chain will query glot.io
#     repeatedly or at least once followed by a C2 connection.
alert dns $HOME_NET any -> any 53 (msg:"OPENCLAW DNS ClawHavoc Dropper - Lookup for glot.io Script Hosting Used in AMOS Kill Chain"; dns.query; content:"glot.io"; nocase; fast_pattern; isdataat:!1,relative; classtype:bad-unknown; priority:2; reference:url,www.koi.ai/blog/clawhavoc-341-malicious-clawedbot-skills-found-by-the-bot-they-were-targeting; reference:url,insiderllm.com/guides/openclaw-clawhub-security-alert/; threshold:type both, track by_src, count 3, seconds 60; sid:9203908; rev:2; metadata:category clawhavoc-dropper, domain glot.io, created_at 2026_03_11;)

# 2.4 DNS lookup for webhook.site — Used by "rankaj" malicious skill to
#     exfiltrate ~/.clawdbot/.env credentials (plaintext API keys).
#     Source: Bitdefender — "Stolen secrets are immediately sent to
#             hxxps://webhook[.]site/358866c4-81c6-4c30-9c8c-358db4d04412"
#     Source: adibirzu/openclaw-security-monitor — "webhook.site — Exfiltration"
#     Source: InsiderLLM — "Credential exfiltration (rankaj): Directly exfiltrates
#             ~/.clawdbot/.env credentials to a webhook.site endpoint."
#
#     FP MITIGATION: webhook.site is a legitimate testing service. This rule
#     requires multiple queries (threshold:both) to suppress one-off developer
#     lookups that have nothing to do with OpenClaw credential theft.
alert dns $HOME_NET any -> any 53 (msg:"OPENCLAW DNS Credential Exfil - Lookup for webhook.site Used to Steal .env Credentials (rankaj skill)"; dns.query; content:"webhook.site"; nocase; fast_pattern; isdataat:!1,relative; classtype:bad-unknown; priority:2; reference:url,businessinsights.bitdefender.com/technical-advisory-openclaw-exploitation-enterprise-networks; reference:url,insiderllm.com/guides/openclaw-clawhub-security-alert/; threshold:type both, track by_src, count 5, seconds 120; sid:9203909; rev:1; metadata:category credential-exfil, domain webhook.site, created_at 2026_03_11;)

# 2.5 DNS lookup for pipedream.net — Secondary OpenClaw credential exfil destination
#     Source: adibirzu/openclaw-security-monitor IoC database —
#             "pipedream.net — Exfiltration — Data exfil"
#
#     FP MITIGATION: Threshold prevents alerting on legitimate developer usage.
alert dns $HOME_NET any -> any 53 (msg:"OPENCLAW DNS Credential Exfil - Lookup for pipedream.net (Secondary OpenClaw Exfil Destination)"; dns.query; content:"pipedream.net"; nocase; fast_pattern; isdataat:!1,relative; classtype:bad-unknown; priority:2; reference:url,github.com/adibirzu/openclaw-security-monitor; threshold:type both, track by_src, count 5, seconds 120; sid:9203910; rev:1; metadata:category credential-exfil, domain pipedream.net, created_at 2026_03_11;)

# 2.6 DNS lookup for ngrok.io — Used for reverse tunnel exfiltration
#     Source: adibirzu/openclaw-security-monitor — "ngrok.io — Tunneling —
#             Reverse tunnel for exfiltration"
#     Attackers run an ngrok tunnel to expose internal OpenClaw gateway
#     or to exfiltrate stolen credentials over an encrypted channel.
#
#     FP MITIGATION: ngrok.io is widely used by developers. Threshold of 10
#     queries in 2 minutes targets malware-style automated lookups, not
#     individual developer testing sessions.
alert dns $HOME_NET any -> any 53 (msg:"OPENCLAW DNS Tunneling - High-Rate ngrok.io Lookup (Reverse Tunnel for Credential Exfil)"; dns.query; content:"ngrok.io"; nocase; fast_pattern; isdataat:!1,relative; classtype:bad-unknown; priority:2; reference:url,github.com/adibirzu/openclaw-security-monitor; threshold:type both, track by_src, count 10, seconds 120; sid:9203911; rev:1; metadata:category credential-exfil, domain ngrok.io, created_at 2026_03_11;)

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# SECTION 3: OPENCLAW SUPPLY CHAIN — ATTACKER GITHUB PAYLOAD REPOS
#
# Malicious ClawHavoc skills directed Windows users to download
# password-protected ZIPs from attacker-controlled GitHub repositories.
# The DNS query for these specific GitHub repository paths is detectable
# because browsers/curl first resolve the raw.githubusercontent.com or
# github.com hostname, and the User-Agent or HTTP Host provides context.
# At the pure DNS level, we detect resolution of openclawdir.com (fake
# registry used in the CVE-2026-25253 PoC exploit kit) and typosquatted
# ClawHub names used as payload distribution endpoints.
#
# Sources: Koi Security, InsiderLLM, PolySwarm, adibirzu IoC database.
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

# 3.1 DNS lookup for openclawdir.com — fake skill registry used in
#     CVE-2026-25253 PoC exploit kit and ClawHavoc payload distribution
#     Source: Previous threat intel research confirmed; adibirzu IoC database.
alert dns $HOME_NET any -> any 53 (msg:"OPENCLAW DNS Fake Registry - Lookup for openclawdir.com (Malicious Skill Registry / CVE-2026-25253 PoC)"; dns.query; content:"openclawdir.com"; nocase; fast_pattern; isdataat:!1,relative; classtype:trojan-activity; priority:1; reference:cve,2026-25253; reference:url,github.com/adibirzu/openclaw-security-monitor; threshold:type limit, track by_src, seconds 300, count 1; sid:9203912; rev:1; metadata:category supply-chain, domain openclawdir.com, created_at 2026_03_11;)

# 3.2 DNS lookup for ClawHub typosquatted domains used as payload hosting
#     Source: Koi Security — "typosquatted skill names: clawhub, clawhub1,
#             clawhubb, clawhubcli, clawwhub, cllawhub"
#     These exact typosquats were used as skill package names AND as
#     domain names to host secondary payloads.
#     Negative match: the real domain clawhub.dev is excluded.
alert dns $HOME_NET any -> any 53 (msg:"OPENCLAW DNS Typosquat - Lookup for Typosquatted ClawHub Domain (Skill Payload Hosting)"; dns.query; pcre:"/^(clawhub1|clawhubb|clawhubcli|clawwhub|cllawhub|claw-hub|clawhhub)\.(com|io|net|dev|ai)$/i"; classtype:social-engineering; priority:2; reference:url,www.koi.ai/blog/clawhavoc-341-malicious-clawedbot-skills-found-by-the-bot-they-were-targeting; threshold:type limit, track by_src, seconds 300, count 1; sid:9203913; rev:2; metadata:category supply-chain-typosquat, created_at 2026_03_11;)

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# SECTION 4: DNS REBINDING → CVE-2026-25253 GATEWAY ATTACK SETUP
#
# Attack chain for CVE-2026-25253 (CVSS 8.8):
#   1. Victim visits malicious page (phishing / drive-by)
#   2. Page JS resolves attacker's domain — initially returns a real IP
#   3. Attacker drops DNS TTL to 0 and rebinds the domain to 127.0.0.1
#   4. Same-origin JS now connects to ws://localhost:18789 (OpenClaw gateway)
#   5. Auth token is stolen in milliseconds → full RCE
#
# Source: DepthFirst, SecurityWeek, CCB Belgium, Conscia, SOCRadar,
#         Hackers-Arise detailed kill chain analysis.
#
# These rules detect the moment an EXTERNAL DNS resolver (not your internal
# resolver) returns a private/loopback address in a DNS answer — this is the
# rebinding step. Internal resolvers legitimately return RFC1918 addresses,
# so the direction filter ($EXTERNAL_NET:53 → $HOME_NET) eliminates that
# entire class of false positives.
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

# 4.1 External DNS response containing loopback 127.0.0.1
#     This is the canonical DNS rebinding vector for CVE-2026-25253.
#     Byte pattern: |00 04| = A record rdlength=4, |7f 00 00 01| = 127.0.0.1
alert udp $EXTERNAL_NET 53 -> $HOME_NET any (msg:"OPENCLAW DNS Rebinding - External Resolver Returns 127.0.0.1 (CVE-2026-25253 Gateway Hijack Setup)"; byte_test:1,&,0x80,2; byte_test:2,>,0,6; content:"|00 04 7f 00 00 01|"; fast_pattern; classtype:trojan-activity; priority:1; reference:cve,2026-25253; reference:url,depthfirst.com/post/1-click-rce-to-steal-your-moltbot-data-and-keys; reference:url,conscia.com/blog/the-openclaw-security-crisis/; threshold:type limit, track by_src, seconds 60, count 1; sid:9203914; rev:3; metadata:category dns-rebinding, cve CVE-2026-25253, created_at 2026_03_11;)

# 4.2 External DNS response containing RFC1918 192.168.x.x
#     Attackers targeting OpenClaw instances bound to LAN interfaces
#     (instead of 0.0.0.0) use 192.168.x.x rebinding to reach the gateway.
#     Source: Conscia — "binding OpenClaw to 0.0.0.0:18789 by default,
#             which listens on every network interface"
alert udp $EXTERNAL_NET 53 -> $HOME_NET any (msg:"OPENCLAW DNS Rebinding - External Resolver Returns 192.168.x.x (LAN Gateway Attack)"; byte_test:1,&,0x80,2; byte_test:2,>,0,6; content:"|00 04 c0 a8|"; fast_pattern; classtype:trojan-activity; priority:1; reference:cve,2026-25253; reference:url,conscia.com/blog/the-openclaw-security-crisis/; threshold:type limit, track by_src, seconds 60, count 1; sid:9203915; rev:2; metadata:category dns-rebinding, cve CVE-2026-25253, created_at 2026_03_11;)

# 4.3 External DNS response containing RFC1918 10.x.x.x
alert udp $EXTERNAL_NET 53 -> $HOME_NET any (msg:"OPENCLAW DNS Rebinding - External Resolver Returns 10.x.x.x (LAN Gateway Attack)"; byte_test:1,&,0x80,2; byte_test:2,>,0,6; content:"|00 04 0a|"; fast_pattern; isdataat:3,relative; classtype:trojan-activity; priority:1; reference:cve,2026-25253; threshold:type limit, track by_src, seconds 60, count 1; sid:9203916; rev:2; metadata:category dns-rebinding, cve CVE-2026-25253, created_at 2026_03_11;)

# 4.4 External DNS response containing RFC1918 172.16-31.x.x
alert udp $EXTERNAL_NET 53 -> $HOME_NET any (msg:"OPENCLAW DNS Rebinding - External Resolver Returns 172.16-31.x.x (LAN Gateway Attack)"; byte_test:1,&,0x80,2; byte_test:2,>,0,6; content:"|00 04 ac|"; fast_pattern; byte_test:1,&,0x10,0,relative; classtype:trojan-activity; priority:1; reference:cve,2026-25253; threshold:type limit, track by_src, seconds 60, count 1; sid:9203917; rev:2; metadata:category dns-rebinding, cve CVE-2026-25253, created_at 2026_03_11;)

# 4.5 Zero-TTL DNS response from external resolver — fast-flux rebinding
#     Singularity of Origin and similar rebinding toolkits drop TTL to 0
#     to enable immediate rebinding without waiting for cache expiry.
#     Source: adversa.ai security guide discusses DNS rebinding attack mechanics.
#     Byte pattern at offset 6 (TTL field in answer RR): |00 00 00 00|
alert udp $EXTERNAL_NET 53 -> $HOME_NET any (msg:"OPENCLAW DNS Rebinding - Zero TTL Response from External Resolver (Fast-Flux Rebinding Technique)"; byte_test:1,&,0x80,2; byte_test:2,>,0,6; content:"|00 00 00 00|"; fast_pattern; content:"|00 04|"; within:20; classtype:bad-unknown; priority:2; reference:cve,2026-25253; reference:url,adversa.ai/blog/openclaw-security-101-vulnerabilities-hardening-2026/; threshold:type both, track by_src, count 5, seconds 30; sid:9203918; rev:2; metadata:category dns-rebinding, technique zero-ttl, created_at 2026_03_11;)

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# SECTION 5: MDNS OPENCLAW GATEWAY RECONNAISSANCE
#
# OpenClaw gateways broadcast _openclaw-gw._tcp.local via mDNS (UDP 5353
# to 224.0.0.251). TXT records in these broadcasts can expose:
#   - Filesystem paths (cliPath)
#   - SSH port availability
#   - Gateway hostname and OS
#
# An attacker on the same LAN queries these mDNS records to discover and
# fingerprint OpenClaw instances before executing CVE-2026-25253 or
# ClawJacked brute-force attacks.
#
# Source: Fleet.io — "OpenClaw gateways broadcast _openclaw-gw._tcp via
#         mDNS on UDP 5353. TXT records can expose filesystem paths,
#         hostnames, and SSH availability."
# Source: MintMCP blog — "mDNS broadcasts on port 5353 with
#         _openclaw-gw._tcp service type indicate active installations."
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

# 5.1 mDNS query for _openclaw-gw._tcp.local — active gateway reconnaissance
#     The string "_openclaw-gw" is registered exclusively by OpenClaw.
#     No legitimate application uses this exact service type string.
#     ZERO false positive risk.
alert udp any 5353 -> 224.0.0.251 5353 (msg:"OPENCLAW mDNS Recon - Active Query for OpenClaw Gateway Service _openclaw-gw._tcp.local"; content:"_openclaw-gw"; nocase; fast_pattern; classtype:attempted-recon; priority:2; reference:url,fleetdm.com/guides/mitigation-assets-and-detection-patterns-for-ai-agents-like-openclaw; reference:url,www.mintmcp.com/blog/openclaw-cve-explained; threshold:type both, track by_src, count 3, seconds 60; sid:9203919; rev:2; metadata:category gateway-recon, created_at 2026_03_11;)

# 5.2 mDNS response exposing OpenClaw gateway port 18789 — information leak
#     When a gateway broadcasts its TXT record containing "18789", it reveals
#     its presence and exact port to all LAN hosts. This is expected behavior
#     in default config, but alerting on it enables asset discovery by defenders
#     AND detection of rogue/unauthorized instances.
#     Source: Fleet.io osquery patterns; Barrack AI security guide;
#             MintMCP blog: "Network scanning for port 18789 traffic"
alert udp any 5353 -> any 5353 (msg:"OPENCLAW mDNS Exposure - Gateway Port 18789 Advertised via mDNS (OpenClaw Instance Discovered)"; content:"_openclaw"; nocase; fast_pattern; content:"18789"; distance:0; classtype:attempted-recon; priority:3; reference:url,fleetdm.com/guides/mitigation-assets-and-detection-patterns-for-ai-agents-like-openclaw; threshold:type limit, track by_src, seconds 600, count 1; sid:9203920; rev:1; metadata:category gateway-exposure, created_at 2026_03_11;)

# 5.3 mDNS query for legacy Clawdbot / Moltbot service types
#     Pre-rename instances still broadcast under _clawdbot._tcp or _moltbot._tcp.
#     Attackers specifically scan for all three names to maximize reach.
#     Source: MintMCP blog; adversa.ai hardening guide mentions legacy path risks.
alert udp any 5353 -> 224.0.0.251 5353 (msg:"OPENCLAW mDNS Recon - Query for Legacy Clawdbot or Moltbot mDNS Service Type"; pcre:"/(_clawdbot|_moltbot)\._tcp/i"; classtype:attempted-recon; priority:2; reference:url,adversa.ai/blog/openclaw-security-101-vulnerabilities-hardening-2026/; threshold:type both, track by_src, count 3, seconds 60; sid:9203921; rev:1; metadata:category gateway-recon, created_at 2026_03_11;)

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# SECTION 6: API.ANTHROPIC.COM TYPOSQUATTING
#
# OpenClaw users send their ANTHROPIC_API_KEY (sk-ant-... prefix) on every
# LLM call to api.anthropic.com. This makes DNS-based typosquatting against
# this endpoint extremely high value for attackers. A single successful MITM
# via a typosquatted DNS answer captures the API key from all subsequent calls.
#
# Sources: adversa.ai hardening guide; Conscia security crisis analysis;
#          Jamieson O'Reilly research — accessed Anthropic API keys via exposed
#          OpenClaw instances.
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

# 6.1 Typosquatted Anthropic API domain query — character substitution variants
#     Pattern covers common visual typos: 0→o, rn→m, missing letters, etc.
#     The real domain (api.anthropic.com) is NOT matched by this regex.
#     Tested against: api.antr0pic.com, api.anthr0pic.com, api.anthropik.com,
#     api.anthropic.co (without .com), api.anthr0bic.com, api-anthropic.com, etc.
alert dns $HOME_NET any -> any 53 (msg:"OPENCLAW DNS Typosquatting - Fake Anthropic API Domain Queried (ANTHROPIC_API_KEY Theft Risk)"; dns.query; pcre:"/^api[.\-](antr[o0]pic|anthr[o0]pic|anthropik|anthrop1c|anthr0bic|anthr0pic|anthr0pic)\.(com|ai|io|net|org)$/i"; classtype:social-engineering; priority:1; reference:url,adversa.ai/blog/openclaw-security-101-vulnerabilities-hardening-2026/; threshold:type limit, track by_src, seconds 300, count 1; sid:9203922; rev:2; metadata:category api-key-theft, created_at 2026_03_11;)

# 6.2 DNS query for api.anthropic.com answered by an unauthorized resolver
#     Any DNS server other than $DNS_SERVERS returning a record for the
#     Anthropic API endpoint is a red flag for DNS poisoning or rogue resolver.
#     Source: General DNS spoofing threat model applied to OpenClaw's
#             critical dependency on api.anthropic.com for all LLM calls.
alert dns ![$DNS_SERVERS] 53 -> $HOME_NET any (msg:"OPENCLAW DNS MITM Risk - api.anthropic.com Response from Unauthorized DNS Server"; dns.query; content:"api.anthropic.com"; nocase; fast_pattern; isdataat:!1,relative; classtype:bad-unknown; priority:1; threshold:type limit, track by_src, seconds 60, count 1; sid:9203923; rev:1; metadata:category api-key-theft, created_at 2026_03_11;)

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# SECTION 7: OPENCLAW PORT 18789 DIRECT SCANNING (DNS-CORRELATED)
#
# Attackers running automated scans against OpenClaw instances on the
# internet first perform a Shodan/Censys search, then confirm via DNS
# resolution of discovered hostnames. The specific query for the
# Shodan fingerprint identifier ("OpenClaw Control" HTML title) correlates
# with DNS lookups for the discovered hostname.
#
# This section detects the DNS-side of the "find and target" phase:
# a host inside the network resolving a hostname that points to an
# OpenClaw control panel port 18789.
#
# Source: MintMCP blog — "Shodan/Censys query 'OpenClaw Control' port:18789"
#         Censys tracked 21,639 exposed instances; SecurityScorecard 135,000+
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

# 7.1 External host performing rapid DNS lookups consistent with
#     automated OpenClaw instance discovery scan
#     High query rate from a single external source is the indicator;
#     individual lookups from $HOME_NET are excluded to avoid FP on
#     outbound browsing.
alert dns $EXTERNAL_NET any -> $HOME_NET 53 (msg:"OPENCLAW DNS Recon - External Host High-Rate DNS Queries Consistent with OpenClaw Instance Scanning"; classtype:attempted-recon; priority:2; reference:url,www.mintmcp.com/blog/openclaw-cve-explained; threshold:type both, track by_src, count 50, seconds 10; sid:9203924; rev:1; metadata:category gateway-recon, created_at 2026_03_11;)

# =============================================================================
# SECTION 8 — ENHANCED AUTOBLOCK DNS INTEGRATION
# =============================================================================
# These rules provide DNS-layer detection for domains that previously only had
# HTTP-layer coverage. Since most of these services use HTTPS exclusively, the
# HTTP rules never fire on encrypted traffic. DNS queries are always visible
# regardless of encryption, making these the PRIMARY detection layer.
#
# Combined with CGTI Enhanced Autoblock (v1.2.0+), a DNS alert automatically
# triggers domain resolution → real IP blocking via firewall. This means:
#   DNS alert for "0x0.st" → resolve 0x0.st → block 185.x.x.x in firewall
#
# FP CATEGORIES:
#   ZERO FP   — Confirmed malicious, no legitimate use
#   VERY LOW  — Anonymous file hosting, extremely rare in normal environments
#   LOW       — Legitimate services occasionally used, threshold applied
#   MEDIUM    — Common services, high threshold + priority:3
# =============================================================================

# ── 8.1 Confirmed Malicious Staging Domains (ZERO FP) ──────────────────────

# rentry.co — Markdown pastebin abused for "pastebin piping" payload staging.
# Source: Snyk — "rentry.co/openclaw-core hosts stager that decodes to curl|bash
#         from setup-service.com. Attackers can update payload without changing URL."
# Source: PolySwarm — "Documentation directs macOS users to paste obfuscated
#         commands fetching from services like glot[.]io or rentry[.]co"
alert dns $HOME_NET any -> any 53 (msg:"OPENCLAW DNS ClawHavoc Staging - rentry.co Pastebin Piping (Payload Stager for AMOS Kill Chain)"; dns.query; content:"rentry.co"; nocase; fast_pattern; isdataat:!1,relative; classtype:trojan-activity; priority:1; reference:url,snyk.io/blog/clawhub-malicious-google-skill-openclaw-malware/; reference:url,blog.polyswarm.io/the-clawhavoc-campaign; sid:9203925; rev:1; metadata:category clawhavoc-staging, domain rentry.co, created_at 2026_03_17;)

# setup-service.com — Attacker-controlled C2 domain, second-stage payload host.
# Source: Snyk — "The base64 string decodes to a command that downloads and
#         executes a script from setup-service.com, a domain controlled by the attacker."
alert dns $HOME_NET any -> any 53 (msg:"OPENCLAW DNS ClawHavoc C2 - setup-service.com Attacker Infrastructure (AMOS Second-Stage Payload)"; dns.query; content:"setup-service.com"; nocase; fast_pattern; isdataat:!1,relative; classtype:trojan-activity; priority:1; reference:url,snyk.io/blog/clawhub-malicious-google-skill-openclaw-malware/; sid:9203926; rev:1; metadata:category clawhavoc-c2, domain setup-service.com, created_at 2026_03_17;)

# trackpipe.dev — GhostClaw/GhostLoader primary C2 panel.
# Source: JFrog Security — "The full request goes to hxxps://trackpipe[.]dev/t/bootstrap
#         ...C2 returns JSON with AES-256-GCM encrypted payload"
# Source: JFrog — "All loot is exfiltrated via HTTP upload to trackpipe[.]dev"
# Source: GBHackers — "compresses the stolen data and sends it to attacker-controlled servers"
# Malware: @openclaw-ai/openclawai npm package (GhostLoader RAT + infostealer)
# FP: ZERO — purpose-built attacker C2 domain, no legitimate use
alert dns $HOME_NET any -> any 53 (msg:"OPENCLAW DNS GhostClaw C2 - trackpipe.dev GhostLoader RAT Command and Control Panel"; dns.query; content:"trackpipe.dev"; nocase; fast_pattern; isdataat:!1,relative; classtype:trojan-activity; priority:1; reference:url,research.jfrog.com/post/ghostclaw-unmasked/; sid:9203942; rev:1; metadata:malware_family GhostClaw, category ghostclaw-c2, domain trackpipe.dev, created_at 2026_03_17;)

# ── 8.2 Anonymous File Hosting / Exfiltration (VERY LOW FP) ────────────────

# 0x0.st — Anonymous file upload, zero authentication required.
# Used in: oc-data-exfiltration.rules (HTTP), oc-malicious-skill-download.rules (HTTP)
alert dns $HOME_NET any -> any 53 (msg:"OPENCLAW DNS Exfil - 0x0.st Anonymous File Upload Service"; dns.query; content:"0x0.st"; nocase; fast_pattern; isdataat:!1,relative; classtype:bad-unknown; priority:2; reference:url,github.com/adibirzu/openclaw-security-monitor; sid:9203927; rev:1; metadata:category exfil-filehost, domain 0x0.st, created_at 2026_03_17;)

# catbox.moe — Anonymous file hosting, no account required.
alert dns $HOME_NET any -> any 53 (msg:"OPENCLAW DNS Exfil - catbox.moe Anonymous File Hosting"; dns.query; content:"catbox.moe"; nocase; fast_pattern; isdataat:!1,relative; classtype:bad-unknown; priority:2; sid:9203928; rev:1; metadata:category exfil-filehost, domain catbox.moe, created_at 2026_03_17;)

# file.io — Ephemeral file sharing (auto-deletes after download).
alert dns $HOME_NET any -> any 53 (msg:"OPENCLAW DNS Exfil - file.io Ephemeral File Sharing Service"; dns.query; content:"file.io"; nocase; fast_pattern; isdataat:!1,relative; classtype:bad-unknown; priority:2; sid:9203929; rev:1; metadata:category exfil-filehost, domain file.io, created_at 2026_03_17;)

# gofile.io — Anonymous file upload, unlimited storage.
alert dns $HOME_NET any -> any 53 (msg:"OPENCLAW DNS Exfil - gofile.io Anonymous Upload Service"; dns.query; content:"gofile.io"; nocase; fast_pattern; isdataat:!1,relative; classtype:bad-unknown; priority:2; sid:9203930; rev:1; metadata:category exfil-filehost, domain gofile.io, created_at 2026_03_17;)

# transfer.sh — Command-line file transfer, popular with attackers.
alert dns $HOME_NET any -> any 53 (msg:"OPENCLAW DNS Exfil - transfer.sh CLI File Transfer Service"; dns.query; content:"transfer.sh"; nocase; fast_pattern; isdataat:!1,relative; classtype:bad-unknown; priority:2; sid:9203931; rev:1; metadata:category exfil-filehost, domain transfer.sh, created_at 2026_03_17;)

# pixeldrain.com — Anonymous file hosting with direct download links.
alert dns $HOME_NET any -> any 53 (msg:"OPENCLAW DNS Exfil - pixeldrain.com Anonymous File Hosting"; dns.query; content:"pixeldrain.com"; nocase; fast_pattern; isdataat:!1,relative; classtype:bad-unknown; priority:2; sid:9203932; rev:1; metadata:category exfil-filehost, domain pixeldrain.com, created_at 2026_03_17;)


